(dialect :applies ("motoi") :note "Engineering report — Motoi-side.")

(report
  :id compat-architecture-specs-2026-07-19
  :date "2026-07-19"
  :author "Claude"
  :status "AWAITING-ALFRED-REVIEW"
  :time-budgeted "10-14h agent time"
  :time-taken "approx 3.5h agent time (efficiency from clear doctrine)"
  :summary "Four foundational specs authored for the Motoi identity SLAT + Rosetta + compat manifest system. All four are SLAT canonical + MD twin. Zero code changes. Zero touching of Motoi 4.0 training. Ready for Alfred review before dependent lanes (A-1 reduction authoring, A-5 Rosetta prototype) commence.")

;; ─── SPEC 1 — R7RS-small Primitive Floor ────────────────────

(spec
  :id A-2
  :name "R7RS-small Primitive Floor"
  :slat "~/code/motoi-scheme/spec/R7RS-SMALL-PRIMITIVE-FLOOR.slat"
  :md "~/code/motoi-scheme/spec/R7RS-SMALL-PRIMITIVE-FLOOR.md"
  :slat-lines 479
  :md-lines 69
  :primitive-count 299
  :purpose "Declared canonical list of 'verbs every variant guarantees.' Bottom of all reduction chains in the identity SLAT terminates here."
  :key-decisions
    ("R7RS-small PURE. Not R7RS-small + a few conveniences. Alfred approved."
     "Every primitive cites its R7RS section per row for provenance."
     "Includes standard libraries: (scheme char), (scheme inexact), (scheme complex), (scheme file), (scheme process-context), (scheme time), (scheme read), (scheme write), (scheme repl), (scheme load)."
     "Includes R7RS-required aliases (quotient/remainder/modulo alongside floor-*/truncate-*) so implementations providing either name satisfy the contract.")
  :status "AUTHORED — awaiting Alfred cosign"
  :surprises
    ("Count landed at 299 records rather than the ~200-250 mentioned in the task prompt. R7RS-small has more primitives than most summaries acknowledge — the count is honest, not padded. The gap between summaries and reality is largely: (a) explicit syntax records (30+ special forms), (b) library primitives collected under (scheme char)/(scheme inexact)/etc., (c) both quotient and truncate-quotient as legal names.")
  :needs-alfred
    ("None. Scope was 'R7RS-small pure' and that's what shipped."))

;; ─── SPEC 2 — Virtual Shape Vocabulary ──────────────────────

(spec
  :id A-3
  :name "Virtual Shape Vocabulary"
  :slat "~/code/motoi-scheme/spec/VIRTUAL-SHAPE-VOCABULARY.slat"
  :md "~/code/motoi-scheme/spec/VIRTUAL-SHAPE-VOCABULARY.md"
  :slat-lines 232
  :md-lines 74
  :shape-count 14
  :purpose "Small standard set of shape descriptors any verb's :virtual-shape can use. Closed vocabulary — expanding requires doctrine memory + Alfred cosign. Small is a feature."
  :key-decisions
    ("14 shape kinds, matching the low end of the task prompt's 10-15 range."
     "Each shape has: :kind, :summary, :declaration-syntax, :slots, :example-real, :example-virtual, :meaningful-on-virtual, :notes."
     "Sentinel design principle documented: virtual sentinel must satisfy the type predicates a caller might apply to a real value."
     ":kind never is the only shape whose sentinel is a control effect (raise) not a value. Used for verbs that don't return.")
  :shape-kinds
    (port record list-of number string symbol boolean procedure promise hash-table bytevector effect-channel never any)
  :status "AUTHORED — awaiting Alfred cosign"
  :surprises
    ("effect-channel emerged as a distinct shape (task prompt suggested it under a different name). Motivation: framebuffer/audio/sensor/actuator/cortex-stream all share the pattern of 'long-lived side-effect resource that may or may not exist on the variant.' Treating them as a family avoided proliferating one shape per subsystem."
     ":kind any is included as an escape hatch with a WARN validator rule (V10) if it exceeds 10% of verbs. This surfaces vocabulary gaps rather than hiding them.")
  :needs-alfred
    ("Alfred to confirm 14 kinds is the right size. Adding kinds later is possible but requires doctrine memory + cosign per the extension policy in the SLAT."
     "Alfred to confirm effect-channel as a family shape (rather than fb/audio/etc as separate shapes)."))

;; ─── SPEC 3 — Identity SLAT v1 Format ───────────────────────

(spec
  :id A-1
  :name "Identity SLAT v1 — Format Spec"
  :slat "~/code/motoi-scheme/spec/IDENTITY-SLAT-V1.slat"
  :md "~/code/motoi-scheme/spec/IDENTITY-SLAT-V1.md"
  :slat-lines 298
  :md-lines 165
  :purpose "Defines the FORMAT Motoi uses for its per-release identity artifact. Extension of the existing MOTOI-SCHEME-REFERENCE.slat structure. Does NOT contain the 459 verb records — that authoring is a separate, held lane."
  :key-decisions
    ("Four load-bearing identity fields per verb: :signature-data, :contract, :reduction, :virtual-shape. Plus :primitives-required as a redundant, validator-friendly index."
     "Legacy MOTOI-SCHEME-REFERENCE-SCHEMA fields (:name, :library, :signature (prose), :summary, :examples, :impl-status, :pure, :complexity, etc.) all continue to apply. Identity SLAT is a strict superset."
     "Header pins SHAs of the floor + vocab SLATs consumed. Rosetta refuses to consume an identity SLAT whose SHAs don't match its local copies."
     "Reductions are lambdas, use only names from the floor or from other verbs in this SLAT, must terminate. Rosetta enforces at compile time via topological sort (V07)."
     "Contract predicates return #t/#f, never raise, never mutate. Same name-resolution rule."
     "Footer includes :identity-hash of the whole file for tamper-detection.")
  :worked-examples
    (safe-divide list/take-safely file/read-lines file/count-lines motoi/quit)
  :validator-rules "V01-V09 fatal, V10-V12 warn"
  :status "AUTHORED — awaiting Alfred cosign"
  :surprises
    (":primitives-required is redundant with :reduction (a walker could derive it) but explicit inclusion enables fast validation and human review. The validator re-derives it and errors on disagreement. Alfred may want to drop it as redundant — I kept it because Rosetta's compile-time correctness check benefits from the explicit list."
     "The worked example file/count-lines uses file/read-lines as its reduction body. This demonstrates the cascading-reduction pattern: a verb's reduction can reference another verb in the identity SLAT, whose reduction bottoms in the floor. Chain-depth = 2 in that example."
     "motoi/quit uses :kind never with :variadic? #t and demonstrates that never-returning verbs still get an identity record.")
  :needs-alfred
    ("Alfred to confirm :primitives-required is worth keeping (or drop as redundant with :reduction)."
     "Alfred to confirm the four identity fields have the right shape. Small tweaks (renaming :signature-data, splitting :contract into more granular pieces) are still cheap now."
     "The 459 retroactive reduction authoring lane (A-1 execution) is downstream. Effort ~40-80h. Needs a dedicated lane with a supervisor. NOT started here — this spec only defines the format."))

;; ─── SPEC 4 — Compat Manifest Schema ────────────────────────

(spec
  :id A-4
  :name "Compat Manifest Schema"
  :slat "~/code/motoi-scheme/spec/COMPAT-MANIFEST-SCHEMA.slat"
  :md "~/code/motoi-scheme/spec/COMPAT-MANIFEST-SCHEMA.md"
  :slat-lines 225
  :md-lines 140
  :purpose "Output format Rosetta produces + rules for validating it + Rosetta's compilation algorithm + variant-side loader contract."
  :key-decisions
    ("Four binding kinds per verb: :native, :reduced, :virtual, :break. Matches doctrine."
     "Per-kind extra fields fully specified: :native has :variant-symbol; :reduced has :reduction + :primitives-required; :virtual has :virtual-shape + :sentinel-generator + :missing-primitives; :break has :reason + :missing-primitives + :policy-rule-id."
     "Determinism contract: :ts-compiled is informational only and zeroed for :manifest-hash computation. Identical (identity-slat, primitive-registry, policy) → identical manifest-hash across time."
     "Rosetta's algorithm documented step-by-step (8 steps). Uses reverse-topological order to bind leaves first."
     "50-line canonical loader implementation included as appendix.")
  :validator-rules "M01-M08 fatal, M09-M10 warn"
  :status "AUTHORED — awaiting Alfred cosign"
  :surprises
    ("The Rosetta algorithm as documented processes verbs in reverse-topological order (leaves first) rather than the naive forward pass. This matters because when Rosetta decides V's binding, it needs to know which verbs V's reduction references have ALREADY been bound (:native or :reduced). Leaves-first makes that a linear pass instead of a fixed-point iteration."
     "The loader contract is intentionally small (50 lines). This means the compat contract is CHEAP for a variant to implement — a variant author reads the manifest and installs 4 kinds of bindings, no policy logic, no reduction walking. All the smart stuff happens at Rosetta compile time.")
  :needs-alfred
    ("Alfred to confirm the M09 warn threshold of 'break count < 5% of total' is right. Higher = variant should extend its registry; lower = policy might be too permissive."
     "Alfred to confirm the loader appendix should live in this spec (vs a separate LOADER-CONTRACT.slat). Small enough that inline seems right; separable later if the loader grows."))

